1017–1069":"1017–1069","1007–1030":"1007–1030","1030–1070":"1030–1070","1030–1089":"1030–1089","0990–1069":"0990–1069","–1062":"–1062","1000":"1000","1053":"1053","1030":"1030","1062":"1062","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","1007":"1007","1028":"1028","1017":"1017","1005":"1005","1069":"1069","1014":"1014","0990":"0990","1089":"1089","before 1030":"before 1030","about 1053":"about 1053","Vernon, Eure, Normandy, France":"Vernon, Eure, Normandy, France","Meulan, Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Vernon Castle, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Vernon, Eure, Normandy, France","Europe":"Europe","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vernon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Vernon in Eure, France, named from the Gaulish element <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + the Gallo-Roman locative suffix <i>-o</i> (genitive <i>-ōnis</i>).","French: habitational name from the same place as in 1 above or from any of several other places in France with the same name and etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Varnon","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Vernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh de Vernon Count of Meulan was born in 1000, in Normandy, France as the son of Galeran de Beaumont Comte de Meulan and Oda de Conteville. He married Emma Basset de Centreville in 1028. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. In 1078, his occupation is listed as monk of bec abbey in Normandy, France. He died about 1053, in Vernon, Eure, Normandy, France, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1000–about 1053":"1000–umbes 1053","1000–1053":"1000–1053","1005–1081":"1005–1081","1014–1081":"1014–1081","1017–1069":"1017–1069","1007–1030":"1007–1030","1030–1070":"1030–1070","1030–1089":"1030–1089","0990–1069":"0990–1069","–1062":"–1062","1000":"1000","1053":"1053","1030":"1030","1062":"1062","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","1007":"1007","1028":"1028","1017":"1017","1005":"1005","1069":"1069","1014":"1014","0990":"0990","1089":"1089","before 1030":"enne 1030","about 1053":"umbes 1053","